[ 37 ] M. Madan Babu , S.A. Teichmann , Evolution of transcription factors and the [ 38 ] M. Butala , D. Zgur-Bertok , S.J.W. Busby , The bacterial LexA transcriptional irradiation on platelet aggregation and behavioral reactions of albino rats , Bull .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27265378" target="_blank">27265378</a>]<br></li>
<li>Copyright 2010 by the Genetics Society of America DOI : 10.1534 / genetics .110.116376 Effect of Translesion DNA Polymerases , Endonucleases and RpoS on Mutation Rates in Salmonella typhimurium Sanna Koskiniemi , * Diarmaid Hughes † and Dan I. Andersson * ,1 * Department of Medical Biochemistry and Microbiology and † Department of Cell and Molecular Biology , Uppsala University , S-75123 Uppsala , Sweden Manuscript received March 5 , 2010 Accepted for publication April 23 , 2010 ABSTRACT It has been suggested that bacteria have evolved mechanisms to increase their mutation rate in response to various stresses and that the translesion DNA polymerase Pol IV under control of the LexA regulon and the alternative sigma factor RpoS are involved in regulating this mutagenesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20421601" target="_blank">20421601</a>]<br></li>
<li>The increased mutation rate observed during derepression of the LexA regulon is completely dependent on the presence of functional endonucleases ( Cho and UvrC ) and the UvrB protein : Previously we showed that constitutive derepression of the LexA regulon increases the number of DNA breaks in the cell ( Koskiniemi and Andersson 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20421601" target="_blank">20421601</a>]<br></li>
<li>This reduction in - galactosidase activity is indicative of a proteinprotein interaction between HilE and HilD that leads to dimerization of the LexA DNA-binding proteins and repression of the sulA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12595445" target="_blank">12595445</a>]<br></li>
<li>With this experimental set-up , we tested the hypothesis of whether any particular combination of slow growth or stationary phase combined with derepression of the LexA regulon ( causing an increase in translesion DNA polymerases and DNA breaks ) and RpoS induction could induce pronounced mutagenesis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20421601" target="_blank">20421601</a>]<br></li>
<li>In conclusion , mutation rates are remarkably robust and no combination of growth conditions , induction of translesion DNA polymerases by inactivation of LexA , or increased RpoS expression could confer an increase in mutation rates higher than the moderate increase caused by derepression of the LexA regulon alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20421601" target="_blank">20421601</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unexpectedly , for two of the three types of mutations where derepression of the LexA regulon caused an increased mutation rate , this increase was independent of the presence of functional translesion DNA polymerases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20421601" target="_blank">20421601</a>]<br></li>
<li>Second , overexpression of these polymerases by derepression of the DNA dam-age-inducible LexA regulon caused a 25-fold increase in deletion rate that depended on the presence of functional translesion polymerases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19525399" target="_blank">19525399</a>]<br></li>
<li>LexA also undergoes RecA-stimulated cleavage in the presence of damaged DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21731505" target="_blank">21731505</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , lysogens of coliphage 186 can be maintained only in the presence of LexA protein , which represses the phage tum ( antirepressor ) gene ( 27 , 44 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12399494" target="_blank">12399494</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">LexA protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>In this system , the LexA DNA-binding domain ( LexADBD ) expressed from a plasmid is used as a reporter to determine protein dimerization .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24187088" target="_blank">24187088</a>]<br></li>
<li>The system relies on a wild-type LexA DNA-binding domain and a mutant LexA-binding domain that , when brought together by heterologous protein-protein interactions , dimerize and bind to an altered DNA-binding site upstream of a sulA-lacZY reporter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12595445" target="_blank">12595445</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DBD of LexA ( residues 1 to 128 ) was fused to full-length S. Typhi LeuO ( residues 1 to 314 ) and used as a positive control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>LexA belongs to the winged-helix family of DNA-binding proteins [ 34 -- 38 ] , transcription factors that bind DNA through a mechanism whereby a recognition helix interacts with the major groove and two loops ( `` wings '' ) interact with the minor groove .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27265378" target="_blank">27265378</a>]<br></li>
<li>This cleavage , mediated by LexA residues Ser119 and Lys156 , is similar in mechanism to that observed for serine proteases ( Luo et al. , 2001 ) and prevents LexA from binding to its specific recognition motif in the promoter region of SOS genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16713610" target="_blank">16713610</a>]<br></li>
<li>This reduction in - galactosidase activity is indicative of a proteinprotein interaction between HilE and HilD that leads to dimerization of the LexA DNA-binding proteins and repression of the sulA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12595445" target="_blank">12595445</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine the role of the C-terminal domain of LeuO in oligomer formation , a collection of sequentially truncated forms of LeuO fused to LexA was constructed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , in order to determine the involvement of the DBD , the LH , and the RD-I central subdomain of LeuO in oligomerization , fragments with single alanine substitutions at six conserved resi-dues were constructed ( Fig. 3 ) and fused to LexA for dimerization analysis .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given the dimerization defects of LexA -- LeuO1-309C ( Fig. 6B ) , it was of interest to know if proteins with single alanine substitutions in the last 5 residues showed the same phenotype .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24659766" target="_blank">24659766</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
